@mdebbar yep, but my feeling is that this optimization is a bug - Flutter is assuming that the platform-invoked copy only happens after a right-click, but this isn't always the case (for example the Edit -> Copy menu).

While it might be possible to implement some workaround in DevTools, this feels like a bug that affects all apps and should be handled by Flutter?

Edit: For some extra context - in the place where this came up for DevTools embedded in VS Code, the clipboard APIs are blocked, so calling them explicitly doesn't work. This is a long standing issue that I thought I'd fixed recently, but it turns out to only work for input boxes or when you've right-clicked for the reason above.

@mdebbar I wonder if the right-click hack is needed at all - could the `copy` event be used instead so it only fires when needed, and always for a copy (right-click or not)?

I just tried this in jsfiddle:

### html

```html
<p>select this text and Edit -> Copy</p>
<p id="target">this text will be copied</p>
```


### js

```js
var target = document.getElementById('target');
document.body.addEventListener('copy', (event) => {
    const selection = window.getSelection();
    const range = document.createRange();
    range.selectNodeContents(target);
    selection.removeAllRanges();
    selection.addRange(range);
});
```

And it seems to work - it's the target text that ends up in the clipboard when I used Cmd+C, Edit->Copy etc.

